In platforms/windows/src/FileID.App/ViewModels/EngineClient.cs at line 1077, replace:

    if (e.Error.Kind is { } ck && ck.Contains("cluster", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
    {
        Interlocked.Exchange(ref _faceClusterAutoInFlight, 0);
    }

with:

    // PAR-111: release the auto gate only on a genuine clustering FAILURE.
    // face_clustering_busy (single-flight bounce) ALSO contains "cluster"
    // but means a pass is still ACTIVE — clearing the gate there breaks the
    // app-side single-flight (Run A's own Complete/Failed releases it).
    if (e.Error.Kind == "face_clustering_failed")
    {
        Interlocked.Exchange(ref _faceClusterAutoInFlight, 0);
    }

This matches the documented intent and the two engine emit sites (commands/face_clustering.rs:388 and :403), both of which use the exact kind "face_clustering_failed".

Apply a BGE-local intra-op override so the CPU-pinned session uses all performance cores, without disturbing the other (vendor-keyed) wrappers. In bge_text.rs::load, after `configure_session_builder(builder)` (line 56), force the multi-threaded CPU count:

    let mut builder =
        configure_session_builder(builder).context("configure session (BGE)")?;
    // BGE is pinned to the CPU EP (chain below), but configure_session_builder
    // keys intra_threads off the BOX vendor, not this session's chain, so on a
    // GPU box it would leave BGE at the GPU default of 1 thread → single-threaded
    // CPU inference. Force the all-p-cores count to match the CPU-EP intent.
    builder = builder
        .with_intra_threads(crate::platform::cpu_topology().p_cores.max(1) as usize)
        .context("BGE intra-op threads")?;

This overrides only the intra-op count (graph-opt level Level3 from configure_session_builder is already correct for CPU). It is BGE-scoped, so mobileclip/ram_plus/etc. keep their GPU 1-thread tuning. Alternatively, parameterize configure_session_builder to accept the intended EP/chain and pass ExecutionProvider::Cpu from BgeText::load, updating all 8 call sites to pass their actual chain head — cleaner but higher blast radius. The local override is the minimal, lowest-risk fix.

In EngineClient.cs, move the PAR-111 gate-release out of the unconditional post-switch block and into the genuine-error branch only, so a benign warning (face_clustering_busy) never clears the in-flight auto gate:

```csharp
case ErrorEvent e:
    if (IsNonFatalWarningKind(e.Error.Kind))
    {
        LastWarning = e.Error;
        DebugLog.Info($"[IPC IN] engine warning: kind={e.Error.Kind} msg={e.Error.Message}");
    }
    else
    {
        LastError = e.Error;
        DebugLog.Warn($"[IPC IN] engine error: kind={e.Error.Kind} msg={e.Error.Message} path={PathRedactor.Redact(e.Error.Path)}");
        // PAR-111: a genuine clustering FAILURE must release the auto gate,
        // else auto-clustering stays suppressed for the rest of the session.
        // Must NOT fire on the benign face_clustering_busy warning (above),
        // which would clear the gate while a real auto pass is still running.
        if (e.Error.Kind is { } ck && ck.Contains("cluster", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
        {
            Interlocked.Exchange(ref _faceClusterAutoInFlight, 0);
        }
    }
    break;
```

This is byte-faithful to the original intent (release on face_clustering_failed) while excluding the new benign busy notice. No engine change needed; the engine single-flight guard already prevents any actual overlap.

Primary: delete line 680 (`LastMergeSuggestions = null;`) in WaitForMergeSuggestionsAsync (EngineClient.Commands.cs) and the now-stale comment above it. The handler still completes correctly on the next reply because Pairs is reference-compared, so Set always fires PropertyChanged for a genuine reply; the reset was a no-op that only drove the persistent sheet observer to the negative empty-state.

Optional hardening (distinguishes "no data yet" from "engine returned an empty set"): a real empty reply deserializes to a NON-null MergeSuggestions with Pairs.Count == 0, while null now means "not fetched / in flight." If any reset is ever reintroduced, make Render() treat null as the in-flight placeholder rather than the negative result, e.g. in SuggestedMergesSheet.Render():
    if (sug is null) { HeaderText.Text = "Looking for similar clusters…"; _rows.Clear(); return; }
    _rows.Clear();
    if (sug.Pairs.Count == 0) { HeaderText.Text = "No likely merges found. (Try after a fresh scan + re-cluster.)"; return; }
This keeps the negative header reserved for a genuine empty reply and never flashes it during a fetch.
